# Delivery workflow

Full detail in `LIFECYCLE.md`. Summary:

1. Pick the lowest-numbered GitHub issue that is `approved`, unblocked, and unassigned. Assign yourself (comment on the issue).
2. Branch from fresh `main`: `task/T1.2-short-slug` (or `fix/issue-42-slug` for bugs). **Never commit to `main` directly.**
3. Implement. Update `TASKS.md` status (⏳ → ✅ with Notes) in the same branch.
4. Run `pnpm check` locally; only open the PR when green.
5. PR: conventional-commit title ending with the task ID, e.g. `feat(osp-core): append-only SoulStore (T1.2)`; body `Closes #N`; fill the PR template. Keep PRs under ~600 changed lines (excluding lockfiles/goldens) — split otherwise.
6. An AI reviewer that did not author the PR will review via GitHub. Reviews arrive as PR comments (often titled "🤖 AI Review — APPROVE / REQUEST CHANGES"; verdicts `LGTM` / `Approve` / `APPROVE` are binding). Formal GitHub reviews are blocked because all agents share the owner account. Respond to REQUEST CHANGES by pushing fixes. After opening a PR, **STOP** — comment ready-for-review, do not merge. Never merge until a non-author reviewer verdict exists and CI is green; merge only by the human or an agent explicitly instructed by the human. See `no-self-merge.mdc`.
7. Discovered work (bugs, follow-ups, ambiguities) becomes a new issue — never scope creep in the current PR.

## Human gates — hard stops

- **Gate 1:** no `approved` label on the issue → do not start.
- **Gate 2:** never execute production actions: deploying to the VPS, genesis ceremony, key generation/rotation, wallet/treasury operations, tagged releases, publishing images, making Atlas public. Prepare them fully (scripts, runbook, dry-run results), then stop and request human approval on a `release` issue.

## Governance CI (keeps docs honest)

A `Governance` workflow fails your PR if: source/spec changed without a TASKS.md update · source changed without a changeset · `osp-core`/`osp-cli`/`spec` import other workspace packages · CHANGELOG.md was hand-edited. Escape hatches are labels (`governance-exempt`, `no-changeset`) — use them only when genuinely applicable and say why in the PR body.

## CI red on main

Stop-the-line: file a `bug` issue (no gate needed), fix it before any task work.
